mall>PMI</small> ）的下降表明该地区正面临衰退。</p><p class="css-1hno3qs e190yofl0">在 9 月 14 日欧洲央行 ( <small>ECB</small> ) 下次会议之前，政策制定者将担心可能出现滞胀（低增长与根深蒂固的通胀相结合的情况）。央行行长克里斯蒂娜·拉加德 (Christine Lagarde) 最近重申，她致力于降低通胀，并“在必要的时间内将利率设定在充分限制性的水平，以实现通胀及时回到我们 2% 的中期目标”。简而言之：<small>欧洲央行</small>更愿意经历经济痛苦的“硬着陆”，而不是未能抑制物价上涨。 </p><div class="css-1bzwzkr eitqf4z1"><figure class="css-qts40t e1197rjj0"><img alt width="608" sizes="300px" srcset="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=16,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 16w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=32,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 32w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=48,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 48w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=64,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 64w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=96,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 96w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=128,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 128w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=256,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 256w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=360,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 360w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=384,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 384w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=480,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 480w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=600,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 600w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=834,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 834w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=960,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 1096w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1280,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 1280w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FNC394.png"></figure></div><p class="css-1hno3qs e190yofl0">问题是<small>欧洲央行</small>面临着飞机坠毁的风险。事实证明，欧元区的通胀与美国的通胀一样顽固。在欧洲，能源成本上涨引发了价格上涨；在美国，他们更受需求驱动。但这两个地方的通胀都遵循类似的路径，欧洲略为落后。现在的问题是，排除波动性的能源和食品价格的核心通胀是否会下降。到目前为止，它仍然顽固地保持在高位（见图表）。</p><p class="css-1hno3qs e190yofl0">部分原因是欧洲和美国一样，迄今为止已经成功避免了经济衰退。去年年底，当许多人预计欧洲经济将陷入低迷时，货币紧缩尚未对经济造成影响，各国政府提供了慷慨的援助以应对能源冲击。服务业呈现出良好的增长势头，工业订单在后疫情时期的繁荣中依然饱满。</p><p class="css-1hno3qs e190yofl0">忧郁情绪正在整个大陆蔓延。全球经济正在疲软，订单簿上有大量空白页。国家对家庭的支持也即将耗尽。能源零售价格仍高于去年危机前；实际收入尚未恢复。根据采购经理人指数<small>(PMI)</small>调查，8 月份服务业活动萎缩。该行业正处于两年半以来的最低水平。</p><p class="css-1hno3qs e190yofl0">正如<small>欧洲央行</small>政策制定者所希望的那样，更高的利率也开始影响欧洲经济。传统上对利率敏感的建筑业也感受到了痛苦。高盛银行 (Goldman Sachs) 表示，吝啬的银行贷款导致每个季度<small>GDP</small>增速下降 0.4 个百分点。与第一季度相比，今年第二季度企业破产率增加了8%以上，达到2015年以来的最高水平。牛津经济研究院的奥利弗·拉考（Oliver Rakau）预测，紧缩货币政策的影响将在今年下半年达到顶峰，一家咨询公司。</p><p class="css-1hno3qs e190yofl0">因此，硬着陆几乎是板上钉钉的事情。但通胀率回到<small>欧洲央行</small>2% 的目标仍有一段路要走。两种力量正在将价格推向不同的方向。一是劳动力市场的情况。失业率仍处于历史低位。尽管企业雇用的工人数量减少，但大规模裁员的迫在眉睫的危险并不存在——部分原因是老板们希望留住在老龄化大陆上日益稀缺的工人。结果，整个欧元区的工资都在上涨，尽管涨幅不足以弥补之前的通胀。</p><p class="css-1hno3qs e190yofl0">拉低通胀的另一股力量正在削弱对商品和服务的需求。在新冠疫情期间，物价增长先于工资增长，导致企业利润随着通货膨胀而强劲增长。如果企业现在发现需求正在枯竭，那么通货膨胀可能会在工资增长保持高位的同时下降，从而导致利润回落。事实上，商品批发市场的价格已经在快速下降，进口价格也在下降。在某些时候，这些较低的价格将转嫁给消费者。</p><p class="css-1hno3qs e190yofl0">这两种力量谁会胜出呢？目前，答案似乎是需求疲软，因为它也蔓延到了服务业。这表明欧元区通胀可能会在相对较短的时间内下降。但<small>欧洲央行</small>似乎并不相信，并似乎准备将主要利率从 4.25% 提高至 4.5%。政策制定者最好保持利率稳定，以便他们能够评估崩盘的危险。 <span class="ufinish">■</span></p><p class="css-1hno3qs e190yofl0"><i>如需对经济、金融和市场领域重大新闻进行更多专家分析，请订阅我们的每周订阅时事通讯<a href="https://www.economist.com/newsletters/money-talks">Money Talks</a> 。</i></p></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 31 Aug 2023 10:21:10 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> /内容/7io1r82smnlm5ge7gmo2vk1ncm8i5lia</guid><link/> https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2023/08/31/europes-economy-looks-to-be-heading-for-trouble </item><item><title><![CDATA[How will politicians escape enormous public debts?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<section class="css-1ugvd2u e18wk22u0"><style data-emotion="css qts40t">.css-qts40t img{display:block;}.css-qts40t .edweubf2{margin-top:0.25rem;}</style><figure class="css-qts40t e1197rjj0"><img alt="美元钞票上的迷宫" fetchpriority="high" width="1280" height="720" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" sizes="(min-width: 960px) 700px, 95vw" srcset="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=360,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FND001.jpg 360w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=384,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FND001.jpg 384w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=480,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FND001.jpg 480w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=600,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FND001.jpg 600w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=834,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FND001.jpg 834w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=960,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FND001.jpg 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FND001.jpg 1096w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1280,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FND001.jpg 1280w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_FND001.jpg 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/image